that, the CIA, the intelligence
agencies,

20:31.363 --> 20:35.801 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
those involved with the special
forces operation.

20:35.835 --> 20:43.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There were just an awful lot of
people who
did various pieces of the
intelligence effort

20:43.242 --> 20:50.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the military effort that
resulted in the
raid itself. But it was -- it
was something

20:50.349 --> 20:58.057 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that -- as an individual
responsible for kind
of overseeing the operation from
the CIA,

20:58.090 --> 21:00.626 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it was a remarkable operation.

21:00.659 --> 21:04.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And a lot of tribute goes to the
bravery and
courage of those who conducted
it.

21:04.096 --> 21:09.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Where is
al-Qaida now, meaning,
is the infrastructure, the
network that Osama

21:09.735 --> 21:12.238 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bin Laden exploited, does that
still exist?

21:12.271 --> 21:19.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEON PANETTA: We have done a
very good job
at decimating al-Qaida's
leadership, particularly

21:19.044 --> 21:20.846 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Pakistan.

21:20.880 --> 21:30.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, obviously, the bin
Laden operation
was kind of the primary effort
to go after

21:30.456 --> 21:36.896 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the spiritual leader of
al-Qaida. And so I
think, generally, a good job at
decimating

21:36.929 --> 21:38.898 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
their leadership.

21:38.931 --> 21:45.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the same time, al-Qaida's
probably metastasized,
as we have seen with other
terrorist operations

21:45.204 --> 21:50.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the Middle East. There are
variations of
al-Qaida that are still
operating very much

21:50.509 --> 21:52.344 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the Middle East and North
Africa.

21:52.378 --> 21:56.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Have we
succeeded then as
a policy to degrade their
network to almost

21:56.815 --> 22:00.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
zero, or, as you mentioned, they
have sort
of sprung out into different
branch operations

22:00.753 --> 22:02.855 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in other parts of the world?

22:02.888 --> 22:07.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LEON PANETTA: The reality is
that terrorism
remains a threat.

22:07.993 --> 22:14.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's metastasized into ISIS.
It's metastasized
into Boko Haram and Al-Shabaab.
And so it

22:14.633 --> 22:19.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
continues to be very much a
threat that the
United States and other
countries in the world

22:19.838 --> 22:23.342 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have to focus on. This is a
long-term effort.

22:23.375 --> 22:27.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have had some success, there
is no question
about it. We have gone after
their leadership.

22:27.313 --> 22:32.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have done well to prevent
another 9/11-type
attack, but there remains an
awful lot more

22:32.918 --> 22:35.487 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
work to be done in order to
protect this country.

22:35.521 --> 22:40.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Five years on,
have we fully
understood the complicity of
Pakistan in all

22:40.125 --> 22:42.061 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
this?

22:42.094 --> 22:52.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEON PANETTA: It's -- it's been
a challenging
period to develop the
relationship with Pakistan.

22:52.204 --> 23:02.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obviously, Pakistan was helpful
in being able
to work with us in many areas.
Certainly,

23:02.114 --> 23:06.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the intelligence area, we
worked together.
On military efforts, we worked
together. But,

23:06.418 --> 23:13.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at the same time, Pakistan was
difficult because
they had a close relationship to
various terrorist

23:13.993 --> 23:21.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
networks, and you were never
quite sure just
exactly where their loyalties
would lie.

23:21.033 --> 23:25.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was for that reason, very
frankly,
that when we were looking at the
bin Laden

23:25.904 --> 23:30.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
operation, which we would have
preferred,
frankly, to have worked with
Pakistan. But

23:30.809 --> 23:35.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
