attends Harvard
University in 2017.

44:29.400 --> 44:33.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's an idea that's taking hold
among more
students, often at elite
schools, but not

44:33.771 --> 44:35.106 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
only those.

44:35.139 --> 44:37.308 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
William Brangham looks at the
broader trend.

44:37.341 --> 44:41.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It's estimated
that, last
year in the U.S., 30,000 to
40,000 students

44:41.979 --> 44:45.383 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tried out a gap year. And that's
a 20 percent
jump from the previous year.

44:45.416 --> 44:47.752 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, what are they, why the
growing interest?

44:47.785 --> 44:52.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To help fill in the picture, I'm
joined from
Boston by Joe O'Shea. He's the
author of "Gap

44:52.757 --> 44:57.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Year: How Delaying College
Changes People
in Ways the World Needs." He
also directs

44:57.495 --> 45:01.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Center for Undergraduate
Research and
Academic Engagement at Florida
State University.

45:01.899 --> 45:03.834 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, Joe, welcome.

45:03.868 --> 45:04.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSEPH O'SHEA, Author, "Gap
Year: How Delaying
College Changes People in Ways
the World Needs":

45:04.235 --> 45:06.037 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you.

45:06.070 --> 45:08.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I think a lot
of our viewers
have this stereotype that a gap
year is for

45:08.906 --> 45:13.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
rich kids to put on a backpack
and travel
around Europe and find
themselves. I know

45:13.644 --> 45:16.781 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's not totally true, so,
tell us, what
is a gap year?

45:16.814 --> 45:18.516 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOSEPH O'SHEA: Sure.

45:18.549 --> 45:21.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are so many misconceptions
about what
a gap year is, and some people
think it's

45:21.285 --> 45:25.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
just waiting around in your home
community,
maybe sitting on your parents'
couch, taking

45:25.089 --> 45:26.958 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a year off from school.

45:26.991 --> 45:31.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we think of gap year as
something very
different, a very powerful
educational experience.

45:31.095 --> 45:36.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a structured, deliberate
and purposeful
experience, in which students
challenge themselves

45:36.200 --> 45:40.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
outside their comfort zones.
Often it involves
traveling or working or
interning, sometimes

45:40.871 --> 45:44.976 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
overseas, sometimes
domestically, but it's
designed as an experience that
accelerates

45:45.009 --> 45:47.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
their personal growth and
prepares them for
college.

45:47.078 --> 45:50.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, could you
give me some
examples of actual gap year
activities that

45:50.748 --> 45:51.782 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
kids are doing now?

45:51.816 --> 45:53.584 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOSEPH O'SHEA: Sure.

45:53.618 --> 45:58.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, City Year, for instance, one
in the U.S.
in which students -- or young
people work

45:58.222 --> 46:03.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in inner-city schools, is a
powerful one and
popular one. Many students go
overseas. An

46:03.728 --> 46:08.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
organization Global Citizen
Year, for instance,
or Omprakash work with local
community-based

46:08.199 --> 46:10.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
organizations in developing
communities around
the world.

46:10.568 --> 46:14.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And students will intern there.
Maybe they're
doing something with young
people or a community

46:14.572 --> 46:17.842 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
role or public health kind of
work. But it
really runs the spectrum.

46:17.875 --> 46:23.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Is there any
research indicating
what impact a gap year has on a
student?

46:23.781 --> 46:25.549 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOSEPH O'SHEA: Sure.

46:25.583 --> 46:29.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have done some research both
in the American
Gap Association and in the
academic world.

46:29.820 --> 46:34.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what's very clear to us is
that, when
students take these kind of
structured, deliberate

46:34.358 --> 46:38.162 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
gap years, that their growth is
really accelerated
across a number of ways.

46:38.195 --> 46:42.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They become better thinkers,
better people
and better citizens. And what is
really interesting

46:42.633 --> 46:45.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is that they perform better when
they get
to college. They are more likely
to go to

46:45.836 --> 46:48.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
college, retain, and graduate
and get higher
GPAs.

46:48.239 --> 46:53.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, I realize
that this
can vary, but there has got to
be a cost associated

46:53.678 --> 46:56.947 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with this. Do we know how much
-- what does
it cost to take a gap year?

46:56.981 --> 46:58.783 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOSEPH O'SHEA: Sure.

46:58.816 --> 47:04.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It really ranges and depends on
what you do.
Gap years can cost as much as
$30,000 a year,

47:04.655 --> 47:09.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but they can also cost very
little. There
are some programs like
Omprakash, for instance,

47:09.427 --> 47:13.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which works directly with
nonprofit organizations
around the world. And some of
them are free

47:13.431 --> 47:15.499 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
room and board for up to a year.

47:15.533 --> 47:18.936 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what is interesting is now
we're seeing
gap year organizations provide
increasing

47:18.969 --> 47:23.307 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
levels of scholarship to
students to support
low-income schools -- low-income
students

47:23.340 --> 47:28.946 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
-- sorry -- and many
universities, like my
university, Florida State,
subsidizing gap

47:28.979 --> 47:30.881 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
year experiences.

47:30.915 --> 47:35.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We are, for the first year,
dedicating $50,000
in scholarships to support
low-income students

47:35.386 --> 47:37.154 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in their gap year experiences.

47:37.188 --> 47:40.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, help me
understand that.
Why would a university, which I
understand

47:40.558 --> 47:43.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they are increasingly
interested in this
-- why would colleges and
universities want

47:43.928 --> 47:45.696 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
their students to do this?

47:45.730 --> 47:50.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSEPH O'SHEA: Well, we now know
very clearly
that this is a transformational
educational

47:50.367 --> 47:52.069 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
experience.

47:52.103 --> 47:54.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, from our side, we know we're
going to
get really good and motivated
and purposeful

47:54.939 --> 47:59.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
students when they come back to
Florida State.
And many universities are
beginning to recognize

48:00.010 --> 48:02.913 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this and see it as a powerful
educational
intervention.

48:02.947 --> 48:09.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The students are going to retain
better, graduate
from the university. And we want
to spearhead

48:09.186 --> 48:13.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this and help signal to students
and their
families and other stakeholders
in the education

48:13.824 --> 48:17.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
system that gap years are an
important part
of the educational ecosystem.

48:17.595 --> 48:21.432 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, I
understand that there
are scholarships available for
low-income

48:21.465 --> 48:25.436 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
students, but isn't this still
mostly the
province of wealthier students?

48:25.469 --> 48:29.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSEPH O'SHEA: Unfortunately,
gap years still
are mostly done by students in
the middle

48:29.774 --> 48:31.542 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
class and above.

48:31.575 --> 48:35.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's a real big problem
for America,
especially since we know how
beneficial gap

48:35.780 --> 48:39.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
year education can be for
students to. And
to get that to scale, we're
going to need

48:39.984 --> 48:44.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
institutions and the government
at the federal
and state level to begin to
recognize gap

48:44.955 --> 48:48.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
years and to federally and --
subsidize those
experiences for students.

48:48.692 --> 48:53.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right, Joe
O'Shea, Florida
State University, thank you very
much.

48:53.631 --> 49:00.571 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOSEPH O'SHEA: Thank you.

49:00.604 --> 49:07.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Finally
tonight, as part
of our Broken Justice series, we
have a "NewsHour"

49:07.745 --> 49:09.547 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
